annotations: Weezy We “F” Baby and the F is for “faded”

Doechii plays on Lil Wayne’s classic trope “Weezy F Baby and the F is for…” First introduced by the New Orleans native in 2004, the moniker has gained more and more meanings every time it was mentioned, on songs like “We Be Steady Mobbin'” and “6 Foot 7 Foot”.

In 2018, Genius reviewed all the lyrics in which Wayne used the moniker.

song.title: Crazy

body.plain:
“Crazy” is a 2022 single by Florida rapper Doechii. She debuted the track live at Afropunk in fall 2021.

It was officially released on April 8th, 2022, marking her second release under Top Dawg Entertainment and Capitol Records.

annotations: None of these hating ass bitches gon’ phase me (Like Jay-Z, huh)

A reference to JAY-Z’s line in his song Ni**as In Paris with Kanye West:

Ball so hard, this shit crazy 
Y’all don’t know that don’t shit phase me

Here, JAY-Z is stating that his haters can’t and won’t throw him off his game. Doechii is simply stating the same. Also, peep the song’s title in Jay’s line.
Awful luxury fucking saved me

Crazy is said to be influenced by controversial American rapper Azealia Banks. The shouting heard in this song sounds similar to that of Azealia Banks’ song Yung Rapunxel. Azealia has a hit song titled “Luxury,” which is what Doechii could be referencing here. Doechii has cited Azealia as an influence, and Azealia was actually supposed to be on the remix for Crazy, but plans fell through after Azealia cancelled the collab and attacked Doechii the same day the collab was announced.

(https://thejasminebrand.com/2022/04/23/azealia-banks-teases-collab-with-doechii-later-slams-her-i-dont-know-who-the-fk-she-is/)
I mean, a bitch off shore, like a Mexico

Reference to the Gulf of Mexico, which is north of Mexico and south of the United States. It is an ocean basin largely known as a beautiful vacation spot. But, it is also a major source of oil for the United States, which ties in with Doechii’s previous line, making this a double entendre.
A bitch gassed like a Texaco

Texaco is an American oil brand owned and operated by Chevron, a gas company.

“Gassed” is also a slang term for the state of being excessively under the influence of marijuana. Alluding to the state of matter in which marijuana goes from solid (bud/leaves) to a gas (smoke). Doechii is a recreational marijuana user, as can be perceived from her hit song Persuasive, which is an ode to marijuana:

She’s so persuasive, that marijuana
She’s so flirtatious
Straight facts, no jargon

Jargon is special words or expressions that are used by a particular profession or group and are difficult for others to understand.

The First Lady is the wife or female partner of the president or other leader of a nation or state, in particular the wife of the president of the United States.
And a bitch been shopping all day, no Macy’s

Macy’s is an American chain of high-end department stores.

In 2003, an investigation was launched against the retailer for the private policing system it has used to deal with suspected shoplifters. The investigation was prompted by a civil rights lawsuit, and found that many of Macy’s actions, from ethnic profiling to handcuffing detainees, was unlawful. In 2006, Macy’s downtown Boston store removed two mannequins and the web address of the AIDS Action Committee from it’s window display promoting Boston’s annual gay pride celebration. The removal was apparently in response to pressure from MassResistance, a local group opposed to same-sex marriage, whose members complained the mannequins were “homosexual.” The removal of the mannequins led to much controversy.

Doechii, as a black member of the LGBTQ+ community, would never shop at such place.
When a bitch been ballin’ all day like Brady
Reference to Tom Brady, NFL quarterback often regarded as the greatest football player ever. Brady is known for his tireless work ethic and fierceness as a competitor.

Contrary to popular belief, the majority of research suggests that there are more similarities between racial groups regarding mental health than there are differences. However, due to systemic barriers that have historically made it difficult for Black and African Americans to accumulate wealth, they are more likely to be low in socioeconomic status than whites. That being said, there are more differences between socioeconomic groups regarding mental health than there are similarities. Stress from low socioeconomic status, for example, typically manifests into certain outcomes, such as substance use and/or abuse. This is likely due to complex and intersecting factors, including environmental and personal factors that make such outcomes either more or less likely (Smyth and Kost, 1998). Doechii touches on the supply chain shortages prevalent since the start of the COVID-19 Pandemic. These have disproportionately impacted low-income individuals, who are disproportionately people of color, leading to stress which manifests itself into the use of substances (such as cocaine) to cope.
https://doi.org/10.1300/J137v01n01_05
It must be so much more to life, if I had diamonds and baguettes

Historically, generational wealth has not been possible for many Black and African Americans because of systemic racism. This is exemplified not only through slavery and its aftermath, but also through more general financial barriers (upheld by white supremacy) maintaining the wealth gap. As a result, Black and African Americans are seen disproportionately lower in measures of socioeconomic status (SES). Additionally, Miller and colleagues note that such disadvantages may further strain their well-being, exacerbating stressors such as feelings that one is unable to to handle difficult situations (Miller et al, 2013).
